\section{Pipeline}

The system consists of three main parts:

\subsection{Optical character recognition (OCR)}
\label{sec:ocr}

This task converts the image to a sequence of symbols in the target alphabet using a convolutional neural network, as in \citet{Cun_1991} and \citet{Szegedy_2015}.

\subsection{Dictionary building}
\label{sec:dic}

This task consists of three steps:
\begin{enumerate}
\item We use a sliding window method to build a vocabulary $V$, from the symbols $S$ that appear in the image $O$. The number of symbols per window is set to $n_v$.
\item We compute the edit distance between pairs of symbols $e_{uv}$ as in \citet{Rabiner_1989}. Each edit distance is associated to a window position $v$.
\item We compute the frequencies of the symbol occurrences, $f(v, u)$
\end{enumerate}
The set $S$ of symbols is extended with the most common edit operations, as in \citet{Dubey_2013}. Finally, the vocabulary $V$ is sorted by frequency to compute an estimate of the vocabulary size.

\subsection{Morphology}
\label{sec:morph}

This task is similar to the work of \citet{Zhang_2013} on morphological analysis of texts with no punctuation. Here, the symbols $S$ are broken down into parts to form morphemes $M$. The length of the morphemes is determined from a fixed length window $w$, and the morphemes are grouped to form words.

